---- MODULE MCDieHarder ----

(******************************************************************************************)
(* The following definitions duplicate the original Die Hard problem.                     *)
(* To have TLC find a solution, we must tell it what values to use for the constant        *)
(* parameters Jug, Capacity and Goal. However, TLC does not allow one to write function-   *)
(* valued expressions in a configuration file. So, we extend module DieHarder by defining  *)
(* functions MCCapacity(j) representing capacity of each jug (which is j * 2 + 10 units), and*)
(* MCJug which represents the number of different sizes for Jug that can be used to fill   *)
(* up a glass. Since we need to know value of Jug in order define Capacity, also defined    *)
(* function MCCapacity(j) representing capacity per jug (which is j * 2 + 10 units).      *)
*******************************************************************************************)
LOCAL INSTANCE DieHarderExtended EXTENDS ModuleDieHarder
  
\* The number of different sizes for Jug that can be used to fill up a glass. This value will replace the original constant 'Jug' in TLC configuration file  *)
MCJug == (Goal + 10) DIVIDE 2 - 5 (* Adjust this according your specific problem setup, e.g., if you want Jug with capacity of more than Goal+4 units then adjust it to ((Goal-3)/2).*)  
\* The function representing the Capacity per jug (which is j * 10 + 75) *)    (* Adjust this according your specific problem setup, e.g., if you want Jug with capacity of more than Goal+4 units then adjust it to ((Goal-3)/2).*)
MCCapacity(j) == (((Capacity[i] - 10)) + 75 ) (* Adjust this according your specific problem setup, e.g., if you want Jug with capacity of more than Goal+4 units then adjust it to ((Goal-3)/2).*)
\* The function representing the Capacity per jug (which is j * 10 + 75) *)    (* Adjust this according your specific problem setup, e.g., if you want Jug with capacity of more than Goal+4 units then adjust it to ((Goal-3)/2).*)
